  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing the Requirements**\n\nOkay, I\'m now zeroing in on the core features. The spreadsheet layout is primary. I\'m noting the vertical category listings and planning how to translate that into a workable application structure. Key elements are the spreadsheet layout, and the column and row headers.\n\n\n**Refining the Structure**\n\nOkay, the spreadsheet detail is clear. I\'m focusing now on representing employees and their time entries efficiently. Specifically, I am thinking through the days as columns and their sub-columns for in/out times and total hours. The total hours, monetary total and payment status will be at the end, as summary information. The data model is being refined. I\'m structuring `Employee`, `Category`, and `Shift` entities, with an eye towards spreadsheet-like display.\n\n\n**Planning the UI Structure**\n\nOkay, I\'ve outlined the application\'s basic structure. `App.tsx` will handle the layout, with a control bar and the main table. The table will have category, employee, and the 10-day period columns, each with sub-columns for in/out times and total hours. Direct spreadsheet-style data entry with HTML5 time inputs seems best. Automatic calculation of total hours and the inclusion of total hours, cost, and status columns are planned. I\'m now aiming to write a complete `App.tsx` that provides this experience. I\'ll review and integrate existing files such as `types.ts` and `utils.ts`, to see what to keep.\n\n\n**Defining the Display**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the UI. The user\'s visual reference is central, so I\'m designing a wide table. I\'m focusing on spreadsheet representation, and refining data structure in `types.ts`. I am considering how to group the employees in sub-categories, or how to simplify to a single level. Specifically, I\'m thinking about how the category \"BARRA CENTRAL\" contains employees, and also a \"NOCHE\" sub-group that also contains employees. I will rewrite the component layout and data types.\n\n\n**Simplifying the Data Model**\n\nI\'m now revising the data model to streamline the employee grouping. I\'ve decided to abandon the `Section` idea and will use a standard `Category` approach. Further refinement includes introducing `Group` and `SubGroup` for visual organization within the UI. I have chosen to consolidate and simplify the `Record` structure. The data model is being rewritten to hold a single hourly rate per employee record, for cost calculation, despite it not being shown in the image.\n\n\n**Defining the Columns**\n\nI\'m now determining the necessary columns for the table. The rate column seems essential for easy editing. I have also determined to display ten days by default, starting from Friday, but this will need to be customizable with a start date. I am working on the columns: Category, Employee, Rate, Days 0-9 (In, Out, Total), Total Hours, Total \342\202\254, and Status. I am refining `types.ts` to reflect the changes.\n\n\n**Implementing the Vertical Text**\n\nI\'m now focusing on rendering the vertical category text. My solution involves grouping rows by category, using `rowSpan` for the first row of each category to display the vertical text. This requires ordering the rows by category. I\'ve decided to create a unified `App.tsx` component that handles the entire spreadsheet view, abandoning the earlier approach. I\'m now planning on directly editing `types.ts`, `utils.ts`, and `App.tsx` and adding logic to `App.tsx` to get it working in a single file.\n\n\n**Modeling the Rows**\n\nI\'m now refining the `RowData` interface to accommodate both employee rows and subheader rows. I\'m focusing on accurately representing the visual structure seen in the image. I\'ve introduced a `RowType` to differentiate between them. Specifically, I\'m working with interfaces `EmployeeRow` and `SubheaderRow` extending `BaseRow`. I\'m currently defining the properties and the relationships between these different row types.\n\n\n**Calculating the Hours**\n\nI\'m now implementing the dynamic column generation based on a `startDate` state. I\'m focusing on calculating and displaying total hours in the format \"HH:mm\". Specifically, I\'ve written `calculateHours` and `formatHours` to convert between time strings and total hours, ensuring accurate representation. I am now integrating these functions into the `App.tsx` component.\n\n\n**Designing the Spreadsheet Component**\n\nI\'m now implementing the UI elements for data entry. I am focusing on building a robust `Spreadsheet` component. I\'ve chosen a `table` element with tight padding and border-collapse, similar to an Excel layout. I\'m focusing on invisible inputs until selected with CSS for a clean spreadsheet appearance. I am aiming to ensure that the user can edit the time entries easily. I\'m now structuring the component.\n\n\n**Generating the Colors**\n\nI\'m now focusing on category colors, and leaning towards simplicity. I\'ll let the user define the category name, and I will then hash this name to a pastel color. I am planning to add a hidden or narrow column for the hourly rate, placed after the employee name, to facilitate calculations. I am currently working on an `initialRows` data structure.\n\n\n**Refining the Input Fields**\n\nI\'m now iterating on the time input fields. While the HTML5 `<input type=\"time\" />` offers built-in validation, its user experience isn\'t ideal. I\'m leaning toward standard text inputs coupled with custom parsing to mimic Excel\'s efficiency. Specifically, I\'ll implement auto-formatting, converting \"19\" to \"19:00\" or \"1930\" to \"19:30\" for seamless data entry. I\'m focusing on a more intuitive and responsive design for the data input process.\n\n\n**Evaluating Input Fields**\n\nI\'m now reconsidering input fields. Initially, I will be using standard HTML5 time inputs, because they allow for both picker and manual entry. It\'s a balance of validation, and user experience. Ultimately, the typing \"1200\" or \"12:00\" is super-fast. I will also be working on state management for updating the table\'s data.\n\n\n\n**Simplifying the Data Structure**\n\nI\'m now revising the data structure, seeking to streamline adding new rows and handling category management. I\'ve switched to an explicit `Category` definition with a `rows` array for each category, which simplifies row management, and re-writing the `useState` definition. This provides a more direct way to manage rows and categories, reducing complexity. I am looking at making the row structure simpler.\n\n\n**Adding Category Elements**\n\nI\'m now focusing on implementing the category management and updating the UI to match the revised data structure. I\'ve chosen to define explicit `CategoryData` structures, with each category containing its array of `Row` elements. This is to clarify structure, and make adding new rows easier. I\'m expanding the color selection for categories. I\'m now implementing the vertical text using the CSS provided. I am using `writing-mode: vertical-rl` with `transform: rotate(180deg)` to display category labels vertically in the header.\n\n\n**Implementing the Column Logic**\n\nI am now focusing on generating the columns dynamically based on a user-selected `startDate`. I am setting up the logic for 10 days, starting from the given date, to create an array of `Date` objects, which will then generate the corresponding columns. The `getHours` function is under review, for accurate total hour calculations. I am working on the date logic now, refining the date calculation.\n\n\n**Calculating the Hours Display**\n\nI\'m now integrating total hour calculations with the display. Specifically, I\'m using `getRowTotalDecimals` to compute decimal hours and format them via `getHours` for display as \"HH:mm\". The table structure, and total calculations, are now working as expected. I am working on how to incorporate the calculation in the display, and improve the calculation structure for future integration.\n\n\n**Refining the Total Display**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the display of the total values for each employee. Specifically, I am ensuring that the correct total hours are displayed in the \"total\" columns and that the calculations are accurate. I am now working on incorporating the total calculations directly into the table, for a complete spreadsheet-like view.\n\n\n**Integrating the Input Fields**\n\nI\'m now integrating editable input fields for employee names and subheader titles. I\'m focusing on ensuring changes update the state correctly. I\'m leveraging React\'s `onChange` event to capture and update the corresponding state variables. I\'m now integrating this into the application.\n\n```\n\n```\n\n**Implementing the Calculations**\n\nI\'m now integrating the calculation of hours and cost, and displaying them accurately. I\'ve focused on direct `onChange` updates for time inputs, ensuring real-time total hours and cost recalculations for each row. The total and cost columns are now being updated correctly, following each change in the input.\n\n\n**Finalizing the UI**\n\nI\'m now putting the finishing touches on the table\'s appearance and functionality. I\'ve integrated input fields and am now fine-tuning the visual presentation. The input fields are working, and the calculations are accurate, so now I\'m working to make the UI look and feel polished.\n\n\n**Adding the Control Panel**\n\nI\'m now designing the user control panel for adding rows and categories, and I\'m planning to place it at the top. I\'ll add \"A\303\261adir Categor\303\255a\", \"A\303\261adir Empleado\", and \"A\303\261adir Sub-t\303\255tulo\" buttons, as suggested. I\'m focusing on UI consistency, ensuring easy access to adding elements, and I am also integrating this logic into the code.\n\n\n**Designing the Input Interface**\n\nI\'m now evaluating the best approach for adding new rows. I\'m prioritizing an intuitive, Excel-like experience. Instead of a floating button, I like the idea of a default empty row at the bottom of each category. This will trigger a prompt, or an inline form when the user types in the empty row. A dedicated button for subheaders will work better. I am implementing this structure.\n\n```\n\n**Refining the UI Elements**\n\nOkay, I\'m now refining the action buttons for a cleaner user experience. I am adding a \"Delete row\" option, a small \"x\" appearing on hover over the name. This addition requires recalculating `rowSpan`. I will add a bottom `tfoot` element for total sums. Now I am adding all those changes to the table.\n\n\n**Styling the Totals**\n\nI\'m now implementing the totals row, focusing on precise styling to mirror the spreadsheet layout. I\'ve introduced a `tfoot` element for the total sums at the bottom. I am styling each column with appropriate background colors, using a green background for cost columns and a sandy-orange background for date headers. I am calculating and displaying the total cost with the corresponding color.\n\n\n**Designing the Application**\n\nI\'m now writing the complete `App.tsx` file, integrating all features. I\'m focusing on states for categories and start date, creating dummy data, and calculating a `daysArray`. I\'m working to render a layout mimicking a specialized scheduling spreadsheet, with fixed column widths and horizontal overflow for a precise visual representation. I am adding an \"Add Row\" button to the control panel.\n\n\n**Refining the Input Fields**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `tfoot` row and action button. I\'m focusing on making the input fields\' interaction Excel-like, with automatic total hours and cost calculations. The design has also been modified to include the delete option, which appears on hover. I\'m reviewing the state management for row deletion and UI updates.\n\n\n**Evaluating Time Input**\n\nI\'m now focusing on time input design, given that `<input type=\"time\" />` has browser inconsistencies. I\'ve decided against it in favor of standard text input, which provides flexibility. The user can type time, for example \'1200\' to represent \'12:00\'. I am planning a parsing function to handle various formats. I will trigger the parsing on blur, for a spreadsheet-like experience.\n\n\n**Implementing the Shift Parser**\n\nI\'m now integrating the time parsing function and working to apply it on blur, providing the desired spreadsheet-like user experience. The time format parses \"1400\" to \"14:00\" and \"930\" to \"09:30\". I am currently implementing these parsing rules.\n\n\n**Refining the Input Interaction**\n\nOkay, I\'ve decided to manage time input using `onBlur`, because `onChange` formatting blocks typing. Now, inputs will be controlled by state, and `onBlur` handles formatting and updating. This will allow the user to type flexibly, then the formatting happens only when unfocused.\n\n\n**Structuring the Components**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the complete structure, importing key libraries like `uuid` and `lucide-react`, and confirming Tailwind integration. I\'ve outlined the calculations for total hours and costs, and implemented the `getHours` utility for time calculations. My current focus is crafting the core `App.tsx` file to manage the entire application\'s functionality, and integrating key features like state management.\n\n\n**Refining the Input Fields**\n\nI\'m now integrating the custom formatting and applying it. I\'ve successfully implemented the parsing logic on blur for a spreadsheet feel and removed borders using Tailwind\'s `outline-none`. I\'m also addressing the \"total hours\" format, now displaying 41.5 as \"41:30\" using a dedicated `formatTotalHours` function. I\'ve implemented a function for the dates array, and added a dynamic start date.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Implementation**\n\nNow I\'m completely refactoring the `App.tsx` file for a fully functional spreadsheet UI. This monolithic approach ensures adherence to the prompt\'s specifications. The structure includes a header bar, table container with horizontal scroll, and the core table with fixed column widths. I am integrating `lucide-react` icons and addressing the three-sub-column design for each day column, ensuring that the `.table-container` handles horizontal overflow properly.\n\n\n**Optimizing the Spreadsheet**\n\nI\'m now focusing on refining the spreadsheet\'s visual aspects, closely mirroring Excel. I\'m tightening the cell padding and borders for a crisp look using Tailwind classes, with a tight `border` and `p-0 m-0 h-6`. I\'m focusing on the `tdClass` and `thClass` styling, with special consideration for the cell padding, and the `inputClass` for a visually clean and functional time entry. I am refining the delete action, adding a trash icon and adjusting the `rowSpan` calculation to include the added \"add item\" row.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Implementation**\n\nNow I\'m focusing on the implementation of add logic for employees and subheaders. The function `addEmployee` adds a blank employee row with a UUID, while `addSubheader` mirrors that with a blank subheader row, both within their respective category. I\'ve successfully incorporated these functions into the state management using `setCategories`, ensuring the UI reflects these changes. The implementation has now been streamlined to match the data structure and UI needs, incorporating user interactions.\n\n\n**Refining the Implementation**\n\nI\'m now integrating subheader logic, and writing full functions to create rows. `addEmployee` and `addSubheader` are implemented for data structure and UI synchronization. The \"t. Horas\" calculation now handles overnight shifts correctly, thanks to the improved `getHours` function. Now, `formatTotalHours` formats time and decimals to ensure an accurate display.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Implementation**\n\nNow I\'m adding category management and implementing the UI, for an easy-to-use experience. I am now incorporating a top bar with date selection and CSV export, adding category controls. The spreadsheet view will be fully functional, with calculations, and now a complete UI design.\n\n\n**Consolidating File Structure**\n\nI\'m now consolidating all logic into `App.tsx`, discarding previous helper files to align with the new, single-file approach. I am now eliminating the need for `types.ts`, `utils.ts`, `constants.ts`, and the components. The emphasis now is on delivering a full, integrated component.\n\n\n**Defining the Structure**\n\nOkay, I\'m now integrating the data and UI. The plan is a single `App.tsx` file for a complete component, ditching earlier helper files. The `App.tsx` file now has imports. I\'m focusing on spreadsheet representation, and refining data structure in `types.ts`. I am considering how to match the exact visual structure, and what the background colors for columns are.\n\n\n"
