  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Examining the Core Problem**\n\nI\'m currently breaking down the core request. It seems the goal is either manual cell height adjustment or an automatic fit based on text content. I\'m focusing on the current implementation to assess how we\'re handling this at the moment, and I\'m planning to consider each option, as well as their advantages and disadvantages.\n\n\n**Analyzing Text Wrapping Options**\n\nI\'m now diving into the implications of text wrapping. My initial thought is that the current `input` elements, with `truncate`, are fighting against automatic height adjustment. I\'m leaning towards either replacing them with `textarea` elements, which can auto-resize, or removing the height constraints and `truncate`. For a more Excel-like feel, an `contenteditable` div could also work. I also considered a CSS resize option.\n\n\n**Evaluating Resize Strategies**\n\nI\'ve been exploring different ways to achieve cell height adjustments, particularly focusing on how to integrate this with the existing table structure. My current focus is on a `textarea` with `resize-y`, which offers user-controlled height changes and fits the requirement for adjusting cell height. I\'m also examining the implications of CSS `resize` on table elements and considering options like CSS variables for row heights, simulating the Excel model.\n\n\n**Implementing Native Height Expansion**\n\nI\'ve made a significant leap. By using a `<textarea>` *inside* a `td`, the `td` and `tr` naturally expand with the text. This natively tackles the height adjustment request. I\'m focusing on refining this, initially replacing `<input>` with `<textarea>` for the \'name\' field. I\'m considering the implications of this change on the table as a whole.\nI\'m also removing overflow:hidden because it may block the resize in some browsers.\n\n\n**Refining Textarea Integration**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a `textarea` solution for the \'name\' field, aiming for both manual and automatic height adjustments. I\'ve integrated a `textarea` with inline style for the `height` attribute, dynamically adjusted via `scrollHeight`. This provides both auto-sizing and manual resize capabilities via `resize-y`, which I\'m confident aligns with the requirement. I\'ll need to explore initial render behavior and handle browser inconsistencies, but this seems promising. I will explore implementation of similar for the other inputs.\n\n\n**Applying ContentEditable Solution**\n\nI\'m now pivoting back to the `contentEditable` idea, but with some modifications to address potential issues. I was concerned about cursor position bugs in React, but the `onBlur` event seems to address this, and allows it to fit text naturally, expanding the row height on wrapping. I\'m prioritizing the `contentEditable` approach to see if it provides an optimal solution.\n\n```tsx\n<div\ncontentEditable\nsuppressContentEditableWarning\nonBlur={(e) => updateRow(cat.id, row.id, r => ({...r, name: e.currentTarget.textContent || \'\'}))}\nclassName={`${plainInput} text-left font-semibold uppercase px-2 break-words focus:outline-none min-h-[28px] flex items-center resize-y overflow-auto`}\n>\n{row.name}\n</div>\n```\n\nHowever, I\'m now going to apply `<textarea>` element for now, for the names.\n\n\n**Optimizing Textarea Implementation**\n\nI\'m now refining the `textarea` approach. I\'ve realized `h-full` and `height` styles conflict; `height:auto` seems to resolve the `textarea` and row expansion. I\'m removing the `truncate` class. The `resize-y` class on the \'name\' field allows manual resizing, and the `td` and `tr` adapt naturally.\nI will test this approach.\n\n\n**Refining Textarea Behavior**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `textarea` element for names, and auto-sizing based on `scrollHeight`. I\'m using an inline style for dynamic height updates to avoid conflicts, while integrating `resize-y` to allow manual adjustments as needed.\n\n\n**Refining Styles and Behavior**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a `textarea` solution and addressing style conflicts. I\'ve realized the `h-full` class is causing issues with the dynamic height setting. I am creating a `nameInput` class or overriding to control height explicitly. The `textarea` within the `td` naturally stretches to the `td` height. I\'m removing the old `plainInput` style, and ensuring the `textarea` height dynamically adjusts based on content and user resize interaction.\n\n\n**Implementing Textarea for Names**\n\nI\'m now changing the name cells to `textarea` elements. It is clear that the only field with text overflow potential is the \'name\' field, which is handled in the code with a fixed width, and now, it will use the `textarea`. I\'m going to implement `textarea` with `resize-y` to allow manual height adjustments and automatic expansion for longer text, and testing it.\n\n\n**Refining Auto-Height Expansion**\n\nI\'m making a key update. I\'m now dynamically sizing the `textarea` height based on its content using `scrollHeight`, combined with `resize-y` for manual overrides. The `td` height is now properly adapting. I\'m focusing on the name input field, where this offers substantial improvements.\n\n\n**Addressing Resize Conflicts**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential conflicts between manual resizing and auto-sizing. My concern is that setting `e.target.style.height = \'auto\'` on the `onChange` event in the textarea might override the user\'s manual resize. I\'m exploring the implications of `overflow: hidden` for `resize-y` and scrollbars; I\'ll need to balance this. I will look at how the `scrollHeight` and `resize-y` work together to address these issues.\n\n\n\n**Evaluating Textarea Refinements**\n\nI\'m currently focusing on optimizing the `textarea` implementation, particularly regarding dynamic sizing and initial render behavior. It seems `useLayoutEffect` might be the best approach for initial sizing, or a `min-height` coupled with manual drag. I\'m also now considering the implications of `overflow: hidden` with `resize-y` and the user experience for scrolling. I\'m exploring various CSS strategies. The use of a `div` with `contentEditable` and `resize-y` is also being considered as an alternative.\n\n\n**Refining Textarea Resize Behavior**\n\nI\'m now integrating a CSS auto-resize approach for the textarea. I\'m focusing on user-explicit height control via `resize-y` and automatically expanding the cell based on text content. The `<textarea>` inside a relative container now dynamically resizes its height, adapting to the text entered, while the user can manually expand the cell height using `resize-y`, which simplifies the height adjustment perfectly.\n\n\n**Fine-Tuning Height Adjustment**\n\nI\'m presently focused on the integration of `textarea` elements. My focus is on addressing the interplay between auto-sizing based on content and manual height adjustments. I\'m dynamically calculating the `textarea`\'s height via `scrollHeight` and using `resize-y` for manual resizing. The initial render height is now key.\nI am making sure that this behavior is smooth.\n\n\n**Refining Content Alignment**\n\nI\'m now assessing how the increased row height impacts the existing table structure. I\'ve realized the `plainInput`\'s `h-full` and `p-1` within `td` ensures that other inputs naturally expand to fill the cell height, aligning text vertically. I\'m updating the padding to `py-1.5` for better text appearance within the `textarea`. I\'m going to test the `textarea` implementation with this update.\n\n\n\n"
